snippet.textDisplay:
Predicting which cars will be valuable is very easy, he gave the answer in the beginning of the video. Look at what is popular with teenagers today, that is the car that will be worth a lot of money in 15 to 20 years when they can buy it.

So that ugly Subaru crossover will never be worth anything. Your mom's Dodge Caravan or any minivan or crossover will never be worth anything. This is because they are not popular with today's teenagers, they are considered dull, boring family cars.

The Nissan GTR, yes. The Hellcat, yes. The Honda S2000, yes. The 2013 GT500, yes. (Also consider it is the last Shelby that Carroll Shelby was alive to have input on, and the last manual GT500. And there's only four thousand of them left. you can get a good one for around 38,000 right now. They will eventually skyrocket in price.)

When baby boomers were teenagers they loved the old Camaros, Chargers, and Mustangs. They increased in value when the Baby Boomers came of age.

The Mark 4 Supra and the M3 you mentioned were very popular with teenagers in the 90s, now they are worth a lot.

Again, if today's teenagers considered it boring, it will be worth nothing in the future. If today's teenagers like it, it will be worth something. There is your answer.

snippet.textDisplay: In the end what makes a classic car is if it does what it's supposed to do very well. The SSR did not, it's rare because no one bought one (I used to sell them). The E30's did, small, nimble and fast, that inline 6 was huge for that car. The AE86 is another great example, it was the best in it's genre (the GTS) and it was a blast to drive. The market was not ready for them in the US so they became rare- they now sell for over $40k if they are pristine.
